05531nam a22010335i 9780520960589DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2014040548  a97805209605897 a10.1525/97805209605892doi  a(DE-B1597)520875  a(OCoLC)909542364  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBX4714.122b.S25 2015 4aBX173.3 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a281.6309222231 aSaint-Laurent, Jeanne-Nicole Mellon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMissionary Stories and the Formation of the Syriac Churches /cJeanne-Nicole Mellon Saint-Laurent. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformation of the Classical Heritage ;v5500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Missionary Narratives in the Syriac Tradition -- t1. Saint Thomas, Missionary Apostle to India -- t2. The Teaching of Addai: Founding a Christian City -- t3. Mari as Apostle to the Church of Persia -- t4. John of Ephesus as Hagiographer and Missionary -- t5. Legends of Simeon of Beth Arsham, Missionary to Persia -- t6. Hagiographical Portraits of Jacob Baradaeus -- t7. Aḥudemmeh among the Arabs -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMissionary Stories and the Formation of the Syriac Churches analyzes the hagiographic traditions of seven missionary saints in the Syriac heritage during late antiquity: Thomas, Addai, Mari, John of Ephesus, Simeon of Beth Arsham, Jacob Baradaeus, and Ahudemmeh. Jeanne-Nicole Mellon Saint-Laurent studies a body of legends about the missionaries’ voyages in the Syrian Orient to illustrate their shared symbols and motifs. Revealing how these texts encapsulated the concerns of the communities that produced them, she draws attention to the role of hagiography as a malleable genre that was well-suited for the idealized presentation of the beginnings of Christian communities. Hagiographers, through their reworking of missionary themes, asserted autonomy, orthodoxy, and apostolicity for their individual civic and monastic communities, positioning themselves in relationship to the rulers of their empires and to competing forms of Christianity. Saint-Laurent argues that missionary hagiography is an important and neglected source for understanding the development of the East and West Syriac ecclesiastical bodies: the Syrian Orthodox Church and the Church of the East. Given that many of these Syriac-speaking churches remain today in the Middle East and India, with diaspora communities in Europe and North America, this work opens the door for further study of the role of saints and stories as symbolic links between ancient and modern traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristian hagiographyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMissionarieszMiddle EastxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aSyriac Christian saintsxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aabgar.  aacts of mari.  aahudemmeh.  aapocryphal narratives.  abiography.  abyzantine.  achristian figures.  achristianity.  achristians.  achurch history.  agod and religion.  ahagiography.  ahistory of faith.  ahistory.  aindia.  ajacob baradaeus.  ajohn of ephesus.  amiddle east.  amissionaries.  amissionary stories.  aorthodox.  apersia.  areligion.  areligious biography.  areligious historian.  areligious history.  areligious scholar.  asacred history.  asaint stories.  asaint thomas.  asaints.  asimeon of beth arsham.  asyriac church.  asyriac missionaries.